  <section id="title">
    <fragment id="1">
      <heading level="1">BASIC Programming Tutorial</heading>
      <para>
        <italic>Hello World Examples and Fundamentals</italic>
      </para>
    </fragment>
  </section>
  <section id="content">
    <fragment id="12">
      <heading level="2">Getting Started with "Hello World" in BASIC</heading>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="2">
      <heading level="3" prefix="1)">Very first BASIC (line-number style)</heading>
      <para>This is the classic form you might see in old BASICs (GW-BASIC, QBasic, TRS-80 BASIC):</para>
      <preformat>10 PRINT "HELLO, WORLD!"
        20 END
      </preformat>
      <list>
        <item><monospace>PRINT</monospace> displays text on the screen.</item>
        <item>Line numbers (10, 20) were used for ordering and <monospace>GOTO</monospace>/<monospace>GOSUB</monospace>.
        </item>
        <item><monospace>END</monospace> stops the program.</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="3">
      <heading level="3" prefix="2)">Modern QBASIC / FreeBASIC (no line numbers needed)</heading>
      <para>Most hobby BASICs allow simple scripts:</para>
      <preformat>PRINT "Hello, World!"</preformat>
      <para>Run it in QBASIC/FreeBASIC and the message appears.</para>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="4">
      <heading level="3" prefix="3)">Asking the user for their name (interactive)</heading>
      <preformat>INPUT "What is your name? "; name$
PRINT "Hello, " + name$ + "!"
</preformat>
      <list>
        <item><monospace>INPUT</monospace> prompts and stores input in a string variable (convention: <monospace>$</monospace> suffix for strings in many BASICs).</item>
        <item><monospace>+</monospace> concatenates strings in some dialects; in others <monospace>PRINT "Hello, "; name$</monospace> works (note the semicolon).</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="5">
      <heading level="3" prefix="4)">Looping the message</heading>
      <preformat>FOR i = 1 TO 5
  PRINT "Hello number"; i
NEXT i
</preformat>
      <list>
        <item><monospace>FOR ... TO ... NEXT</monospace> repeats a block.</item>
        <item><monospace>;</monospace> after <monospace>PRINT</monospace> joins printed items with a space in many BASICs.</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="6">
      <heading level="3" prefix="5)">Conditional hello</heading>
      <preformat>INPUT "Do you want a greeting (Y/N)? "; ans$
IF UCASE$(ans$) = "Y" THEN
  PRINT "Hello there!"
ELSE
  PRINT "OK, goodbye."
END IF
</preformat>
      <list>
        <item><monospace>IF ... THEN ... ELSE</monospace> controls flow.</item><item><monospace>UCASE$</monospace> converts to uppercase (dialect-dependent).</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="7">
      <heading level="3" prefix="6)">Using a subroutine (GOSUB) – classic style</heading>
      <preformat>10 GOSUB 100
20 END
100 PRINT "Hello from subroutine!"
110 RETURN
</preformat>
      <list>
        <item><monospace>GOSUB</monospace> jumps to a subroutine line; <monospace>RETURN</monospace> comes back.</item>
        <item>Modern dialects prefer <monospace>SUB</monospace>/<monospace>FUNCTION</monospace> instead.</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="8">
      <heading level="3" prefix="7)">VB.NET console example (Visual Basic – .NET)</heading>
      <para>If you’re using Visual Basic .NET (different but related language):</para>
      <preformat>Module Program
    Sub Main()
        Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!")
    End Sub
End Module
</preformat>
      <list>
        <item>Use Visual Studio or <monospace>dotnet</monospace> tools to run <monospace>.vb</monospace> projects.</item>
      </list>
    </fragment>
    <fragment id="9"><heading level="2">Quick Reference (commands)</heading><table><row part="header"><cell>Command</cell><cell>Purpose</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>PRINT</monospace></cell><cell>Display text or variables</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>INPUT</monospace></cell><cell>Read user input</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>LET</monospace></cell><cell>Assign a value (often optional)</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>IF ... THEN ... ELSE</monospace></cell><cell>Conditional branching</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>FOR ... NEXT</monospace></cell><cell>Loop with counter</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>WHILE ... WEND</monospace></cell><cell>Loop while condition true (some dialects)</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>GOTO</monospace>, <monospace>GOSUB</monospace>, <monospace>RETURN</monospace></cell><cell>Old-style jumps/subroutines</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>SUB</monospace> / <monospace>FUNCTION</monospace></cell><cell>Modern subroutines / functions (VB.NET, FreeBASIC)</cell></row><row><cell><monospace>REM</monospace> or <monospace>'</monospace></cell><cell>Comment</cell></row></table></fragment><fragment id="10"><heading level="2">Notes &amp; common pitfalls</heading><list><item>
<para><bold>Dialect differences:</bold> BASIC has many dialects (QBASIC, FreeBASIC, Visual Basic .NET, BBC BASIC, etc.). Syntax for string concatenation, functions and program structure can vary.</para>
</item><item>
<para><bold>Strings vs numbers:</bold> In older BASICs strings often have a <monospace>$</monospace> suffix (e.g., <monospace>name$</monospace>). If you forget this you may get a type error.</para>
</item><item>
<para><bold>Line numbers:</bold> Modern BASICs usually don’t require them; they’re only for older interpreters.</para>
</item><item>
<para><bold>Case sensitivity:</bold> BASIC is usually <bold>not</bold> case-sensitive for keywords (<monospace>print</monospace>, <monospace>PRINT</monospace> both work) but string comparisons may be case-sensitive unless you normalize (e.g., <monospace>UCASE$</monospace>).</para>
</item><item>
<para><bold>Running old BASIC:</bold> To run QBASIC/GW-BASIC on modern OSes you may need DOSBox or an interpreter/emulator. FreeBASIC is a modern compiler that runs on modern systems.</para>
</item></list></fragment><fragment id="11"><heading level="2">Short examples to copy-paste</heading><para>Classic:</para><preformat>10 PRINT "HELLO, WORLD!"
20 END
</preformat><para>Interactive:</para><preformat>INPUT "Your name: "; user$
PRINT "Hello, "; user$; " — welcome!"
</preformat><para>VB.NET:</para>
    <preformat>Module Program
    Sub Main()
        Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!")
    End Sub
End Module</preformat>
      <block label="warning">
        <para>⚠️ Do not assume code from one BASIC dialect will run unchanged in another. If you copy an example and get syntax errors, check which BASIC dialect/interpreter you’re using and consult that dialect’s quick reference.</para>
      </block>
    </fragment>
